Fierce cyclone with winds from 140 to 155 miles per hour and torrential rain smashed into Bangladesh’s border with India on Thursday, November 15, 2007.
The eye of the cyclone named, Sidr, was racing north.
It is the worst storm in that area since 1991.
Officials in both Bangladesh and India have been racing to evacuate hundreds of thousands of people in the last 48 hours.
The unofficial death toll as of Friday was 167 with many more expected.
The United States has been stockpiling emergency supplies, shelters, and wave barriers, which should significantly help save lives.
